JAVASCRIPT.TEXT:
The ability to return from a function in the middle of a sequence of statements destroys this property and thus necessitates additional stack management which we shall now explain. Consider the following body of a function f:
x = 42; if (x > 0) { return x; } else { ... }; x = x + 1;
The evaluation of this code starts in ev_sequence_start by saving the current continuation, which is the label return_undefined which was setup in compound_apply and then jumping to ev_sequence. We then evaluate each statement in the sequence in a loop. Each turn of the loop, we place the first of the remaining statements in the sequence in comp. Then, like we did when evaluating the argument list, we save unev (the list of statements) and env, and install ev_sequence_continue as the continuation before jumping to the dispatcher to evaluate the statement in comp.
